<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<exercises xml:id="sec-kinematics-problems" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
<title>Additional Problems</title>

<exercise>
  <statement>
    <p>
      Prove <xref ref="thm-derivatives-of-polar-vectors"/>.
    </p>
  </statement>

  <hint>
    <p>
      Switch back to Cartesian coordinates and use the product rule of differentiation.
      Then, switch back to polar coordinates and use the definitions of the unit vectors in terms of Cartesian coordinates.
    </p>
  </hint>

  <solution>
    <p>
      <md>
        <mrow>\dv{t} \vu{r} \amp = \dv{t} (\cos\theta \vu{x} + \sin\theta \vu{y})</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = -\sin\theta \dv{\theta}{t} \vu{x} + \cos\theta \dv{\theta}{t} \vu{y}</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = \dv{\theta}{t} (-\sin\theta \vu{x} + \cos\theta \vu{y})</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = \dv{\theta}{t} \vu{\theta}</mrow>
      </md>,
      and similarly,
      <md>
        <mrow>\dv{t} \vu{\theta} \amp = \dv{t} (-\sin\theta \vu{x} + \cos\theta \vu{y})</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = -\cos\theta \dv{\theta}{t} \vu{x} - \sin\theta \dv{\theta}{t} \vu{y}</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = -\dv{\theta}{t} (\cos\theta \vu{x} + \sin\theta \vu{y})</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = -\dv{\theta}{t} \vu{r}</mrow>
      </md>.
    </p>
  </solution>
</exercise>

<exercisegroup xml:id="ex-the-usb-throw">
<title>The USB throw</title>

<introduction>
  <p>
    It is 11:58 PM, and your group project is due at midnight.
    The campus Wi-Fi has crashed, so you have loaded the final project onto a USB flash drive.
    You are standing outside your partner's dorm, trying to throw the flash drive through their slightly open window.
  </p>

  <p>
    The window is located at a horizontal distance <m>d</m> and a vertical height <m>h</m> from the release point of your hand.
    You can throw the drive with a set initial speed <m>v_0</m>.
    Now you just need the perfect angle <m>\theta</m>.
  </p>
</introduction>

<exercise>
  <statement>
    <p>
      Construct an expression for the trajectory of the flash drive, <m>y(x)</m>, in terms of <m>v_0</m>, <m>\tan \theta</m>, and the acceleration due to gravity <m>g</m>.
    </p>
  </statement>

  <hint>
    <p>
      This trigonometric identity will come in handy:
      <me>
        \frac{1}{\cos^2\theta} = 1 + \tan^2\theta
      </me>.
    </p>
  </hint>

  <hint>
    <p>
      Begin with the standard equations for projectile motion,
      <md>
        <mrow>x(t) \amp = v_0\cos\theta t</mrow>
        <mrow>y(t) \amp = v_0\sin\theta t - \frac{1}{2}gt^2</mrow>
      </md>.
      Then isolate <m>t</m> in the first equation and substitute it into the second equation to get an expression for <m>y</m> in terms of <m>x</m>.
    </p>
  </hint>

  <solution>
    <p>
      Solving for <m>t</m> in the first equation gives us <m>t = \frac{x}{v_0\cos\theta}</m>.
      Substituting this into the second equation gives us
      <md>
        <mrow>y(x) \amp = v_0\sin\theta \cdot \frac{x}{v_0\cos\theta} - \frac{1}{2}g\left(\frac{x}{v_0\cos\theta}\right)^2</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = x\tan\theta - \frac{gx^2}{2v_0^2\cos^2\theta}</mrow>
      </md>.
      Finally, using the trigonometric identity, we can rewrite this as
      <md>
        <mrow>y(x) \amp = x\tan\theta - \frac{gx^2}{2v_0^2}(1 + \tan^2\theta)</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = -\frac{gx^2}{2v_0^2}\tan^2\theta + x\tan\theta - \frac{gx^2}{2v_0^2}</mrow>
      </md>,
      which is a quadratic function of <m>\tan\theta</m>.
    </p>
  </solution>
</exercise>

<exercise>
  <statement>
    <p>
      Under what conditions on <m>v_0</m>, <m>d</m>, and <m>h</m> will there be a solution for <m>\theta</m> such that the flash drive goes through the window?
    </p>
  </statement>

  <hint>
    <p>
      The discriminant of a quadratic equation must be non-negative for there to be a real solution.
    </p>
  </hint>

  <solution>
    <p>
      First, the equation we need to solve is <m>y(d) = h</m>.
      Plugging in the expression for <m>y(x)</m> gives us
      <md>
        <mrow>h \amp = -\frac{gd^2}{2v_0^2}\tan^2\theta + d\tan\theta - \frac{gd^2}{2v_0^2}</mrow>
        <mrow>\implies 0 \amp = -\frac{gd^2}{2v_0^2}\tan^2\theta + d\tan\theta - \qty(h + \frac{gd^2}{2v_0^2})</mrow>
      </md>.
      The discriminant of <m>a\tan^2\theta + b\tan\theta + c</m> is <m>\Delta = b^2 - 4ac</m>, so in our case, the discriminant is
      <me>
        \Delta = d^2 - 4\qty(-\frac{gd^2}{2v_0^2})\qty(-h - \frac{gd^2}{2v_0^2})
      </me>.
      Therefore, there will be a solution for <m>\theta</m> if and only if
      <me>
        d^2 - 4\qty(-\frac{gd^2}{2v_0^2})\qty(-h - \frac{gd^2}{2v_0^2}) \geq 0
      </me>.
      Rearranging this inequality gives us
      <me>
        v_0^4 - 2ghv_0^2 - g^2d^2 \geq 0
      </me>.
      Most likely, this will not be zero, meaning there will be two distinct solutions for <m>\theta</m>.
      If this seems confusing, graph <m>y(d)</m> for the two solutions (given some specific values of <m>v_0</m>, <m>d</m>, and <m>h</m>) to see how the two parabolas both pass through the point <m>(d, h)</m>.
    </p>
  </solution>
</exercise>

<exercise>
  <statement>
    <p>
      Come up with one set of parameters such that there's only one angle that reaches the window, regardless of the initial speed.
    </p>
  </statement>

  <solution>
    <p>
      There will be only one angle if the discriminant is zero, i.e.,
      <me>
        d^2 - 4\qty(-\frac{gd^2}{2v_0^2})\qty(-h - \frac{gd^2}{2v_0^2}) = 0
      </me>.
      If we factor out <m>d^2</m>, we get
      <me>
        d^2\qty[1 - 4\qty(-\frac{g}{2v_0^2})\qty(-h - \frac{gd^2}{2v_0^2})] = 0
      </me>.
      One obvious way to satisfy this equation is to set <m>d = 0</m>, which means the window is directly above the release point of your hand.
      Another way to satisfy this equation is to set the expression in the brackets equal to zero, which gives us
      <me>
        1 - 4\qty(-\frac{g}{2v_0^2})\qty(-h - \frac{gd^2}{2v_0^2}) = 0 \implies h = \frac{v_0^2}{2g} - \frac{gd^2}{2v_0^2}
      </me>.
      This gives us a relationship between <m>h</m>, <m>d</m>, and <m>v_0</m> such that there will be only one angle that reaches the window.
    </p>
  </solution>
</exercise>
</exercisegroup>

<exercise>
  <statement>
    <p>
      A string quartet is rehearsing in a practice room on campus.
      The violist, as always, forgot their rosin, so they decide to borrow some from the violinist.
      Assuming the violinist throws the rosin with an initial speed of <m>v_0</m> at an angle of <m>\theta</m>, what's the ideal angle <m>\theta</m> that maximizes the horizontal distance traveled by the rosin?
    </p>
  </statement>

  <hint>
    <p>
      You may need to use the double angle formula for sine <m>\sin 2\theta = 2\sin\theta \cos\theta</m>.
    </p>
  </hint>

  <solution>
    <p>
      We need to find the horizontal distance traveled by the rosin.
      When it arrives, the height is zero, so we can set
      <me>
        0 = -\frac{1}{2}gt^2 + v_y(0) t = -\frac{1}{2}gt^2 + v_0\sin\theta t
      </me>.
      This gives us two solutions for <m>t</m>: <m>t = 0</m> (when the rosin is released) and <m>t = \frac{2v_0\sin\theta}{g}</m> (when the rosin lands).
      Plugging the latter solution into the equation for horizontal position gives us
      <me>
        x = v_x(0) t = v_0\cos\theta \cdot \frac{2v_0\sin\theta}{g} = \frac{v_0^2}{g} \cdot 2\sin\theta \cos\theta = \frac{v_0^2}{g} \sin 2\theta
      </me>.
      The maximum value of <m>\sin 2\theta</m> is 1, which occurs when <m>2\theta = 90^\circ</m>, so the ideal angle to throw the rosin is <m>\theta = 45^\circ</m>.
    </p>
  </solution>
</exercise>

<exercise>
  <statement>
    <p>
      Draw a unit circle on the Cartesian plane, and then draw a line segment from the origin to a point on the unit circle.
      The angle between the line segment and the positive x-axis is <m>\theta</m>.
      The vertical and horizontal components of the line segment are <m>\sin\theta</m> and <m>\cos\theta</m>, respectively.
    </p>

    <p>
      Increase the angle <m>\theta</m> by a small amount <m>\dd{\theta}</m>.
      What are the vertical and horizontal components of the change in the line segment?
    </p>

    <p>
      Using this, show that
      <md>
        <mrow>\dv{\theta} \sin\theta \amp = \cos\theta</mrow>
        <mrow>\dv{\theta} \cos\theta \amp = -\sin\theta</mrow>
      </md>.
    </p>
  </statement>

  <hint>
    <p>
      The arc formed between the two angles can be approximated by a straight line.
      This allows us to use similar triangles to find the vertical and horizontal components of the change in the line segment.
    </p>
  </hint>
</exercise>

<exercise>
  <statement>
    <p>
      Suppose the van in our storyline was allowed to drive radially and tangentially in the "Founder's Quad Traffic Circle".
      Recall that in polar coordinates, the position of the van is given by <m>\vb{r}(t) = r\vu{r}</m>, where <m>r</m> is the distance from the center of the traffic circle and <m>\vu{r}</m> is the unit vector pointing radially outward from the center of the traffic circle.
      Show that the acceleration of the van can be written as
      <me>
        \vb{a} = \qty(\dv[2]{r}{t} - r\qty(\dv{\theta}{t})^2)\vu{r} + \qty(r\dv[2]{\theta}{t} + 2\dv{r}{t}\dv{\theta}{t})\vu{\theta}
      </me>.
      One of these terms is the centripetal acceleration, which is responsible for keeping the van moving in a circle.
      The other is called the <term>coriolis acceleration</term>, which is responsible for the van's tendency to "slide outward" when it tries to turn.
    </p>
  </statement>

  <solution>
    <p>
      This is just brute force differentiation, using the product rule and the results from <xref ref="thm-derivatives-of-polar-vectors"/>.
      First, we compute the velocity of the van:
      <md>
        <mrow>\vb{v} \amp = \dv{t} \vb{r} = \dv{t} (r\vu{r}) </mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = \dv{r}{t}\vu{r} + r\dv{\vu{r}}{t} </mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = \dv{r}{t}\vu{r} + r\dv{\theta}{t}\vu{\theta}</mrow>
      </md>.
      Then the acceleration is
      <md>
        <mrow>\vb{a} \amp = \dv{t} \vb{v} = \dv{t} \qty(\dv{r}{t}\vu{r} + r\dv{\theta}{t}\vu{\theta})</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = \dv[2]{r}{t} \vu{r} + \dv{r}{t}\dv{\vu{r}}{t} + \dv{r}{t}\dv{\theta}{t}\vu{\theta} + r\dv[2]{\theta}{t}\vu{\theta} + r\dv{\theta}{t}\dv{\vu{\theta}}{t}</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = \dv[2]{r}{t} \vu{r} + \dv{r}{t}\dv{\theta}{t}\vu{\theta} + \dv{r}{t}\dv{\theta}{t}\vu{\theta} + r\dv[2]{\theta}{t}\vu{\theta} - r\qty(\dv{\theta}{t})^2\vu{r}</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = \qty(\dv[2]{r}{t} - r\qty(\dv{\theta}{t})^2)\vu{r} + \qty(r\dv[2]{\theta}{t} + 2\dv{r}{t}\dv{\theta}{t})\vu{\theta}</mrow>
      </md>
    </p>
  </solution>
</exercise>

<exercisegroup xml:id="ex-integration-techniques">
<title>Integration techniques</title>

<introduction>
  <p>
    This set of exercises will introduce you to a few integration techniques that are commonly used in physics.
  </p>

  <p>
    We know that the integral is used to measure the accumulation of a quantity.
    For instance, the integral of velocity with respect to time gives us the total displacement, as denoted by
    <me>
      x_f - x_i = \int_{t_i}^{t_f} v(t) \dd{t}
    </me>.
    A common notation you will see is the <term>antiderivative</term>, where we write
    <me>
      \int v(t) \dd{t} = V(t) + C
    </me>,
    in which <m>V(t)</m> is any function such that <m>\dv{t} V(t) = v(t)</m>, and <m>C</m> is an arbitrary constant of integration.
    This notation is useful when we don't have specific limits of integration, and we just want to find a general expression for the integral.
  </p>

  <p>
    The fact that the derivative of the antiderivative gives us back the original expression in the integral (called the <term>integrand</term>) is the <term>fundamental theorem of calculus</term>.
  </p>
</introduction>

<exercise>
  <statement>
    <p>
      Using the power rule of differentiation,
      <me>
        \dv{t} t^n = nt^{n-1}
      </me>,
      find the antiderivative of <m>t^n</m>.
    </p>
  </statement>

  <solution>
    <p>
      <me>
        \int t^n \dd{t} = \frac{t^{n+1}}{n+1} + C
      </me>.
    </p>
  </solution>
</exercise>

<exercise>
  <statement>
    <p>
      Using the fact that
      <md>
        <mrow> \dv{\theta} \sin\theta \amp = \cos\theta </mrow>
        <mrow> \dv{\theta} \cos\theta \amp = -\sin\theta </mrow>
      </md>,
      find the antiderivative of <m>\sin\theta</m> and <m>\cos\theta</m>.
    </p>
  </statement>

  <solution>
    <p>
      <md>
        <mrow> \int \sin\theta \dd{\theta} \amp = -\cos\theta + C </mrow>
        <mrow> \int \cos\theta \dd{\theta} \amp = \sin\theta + C </mrow>
      </md>.
    </p>
  </solution>
</exercise>

<exercise>
  <statement>
    <p>
      Recall from the chain rule of differentiation that
      <me>
        \dv{t} f(g(t)) = \dv{f}{g} \cdot \dv{g}{t}
      </me>.
      There is a technique of integration called <term>integration by substitution</term> that is based on the chain rule.
      Suppose we have the integral
      <me>
        \int 2x \sin(x^2) \dd{x}
      </me>.
      Make the substitution <m>u = x^2</m>, and then find the antiderivative of the integrand with respect to <m>x</m>.
    </p>
  </statement>

  <solution>
    <p>
      If we let <m>u = x^2</m>, then <m>\dv{u}{x} = 2x</m>, so <m>\dd{u} = 2x \dd{x}</m>.
      Therefore, the integral becomes
      <me>
        \int \underbrace{\sin(x^2)}_{\sin(u)} \underbrace{2x \dd{x}}_{\dd{u}} = \int \sin u \dd{u} = -\cos u + C = -\cos(x^2) + C
      </me>.
    </p>
  </solution>
</exercise>

<exercise>
  <statement>
    <p>
      Use the substitution <m>x = \tan\theta</m> to find the antiderivative of <m>\frac{1}{1 + x^2}</m>. The derivative of <m>\tan\theta</m> is <m>\sec^2\theta</m>.
    </p>
  </statement>

  <hint>
    <p>
      Use the trigonometric identity <m>1 + \tan^2\theta = \sec^2\theta</m> to simplify the integral after making the substitution.
    </p>
  </hint>

  <solution>
    <p>
      If we let <m>x = \tan\theta</m>, then <m>\dv{x}{\theta} = \sec^2\theta</m>, so <m>\dd{x} = \sec^2\theta \dd{\theta}</m>.
      Therefore, the integral becomes
      <md>
        <mrow>\int \frac{1}{1 + x^2} \dd{x} \amp = \int \frac{1}{1 + \tan^2\theta} \sec^2\theta \dd{\theta}</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = \int \frac{1}{\sec^2\theta} \sec^2\theta \dd{\theta}</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = \int 1 \dd{\theta} = \theta + C = \arctan x + C</mrow>
      </md>.
    </p>
  </solution>
</exercise>

<exercise>
  <statement>
    <p>
      Recall from the product rule of differentiation that
      <me>
        \dv{t} (f(t)g(t)) = f(t) \dv{g}{t} + g(t) \dv{f}{t}
      </me>,
      or more succinctly,
      <me>
        \dv{t} (fg) = f \dot{g} + g \dot{f}
      </me>.
      If we integrate both sides of this equation with respect to time, we get
      <me>
        \int \dv{t} (fg) \dd{t} = \int f \dot{g} \dd{t} + \int g \dot{f} \dd{t}
      </me>.
      Using the fundamental theorem of calculus, we can simplify the left-hand side to get
      <me>
        fg = \int f \dot{g} \dd{t} + \int g \dot{f} \dd{t}
      </me>.
      Rearranging this equation gives us the formula for <term>integration by parts</term>:
      <me>
        \int f \dot{g} \dd{t} = fg - \int g \dot{f} \dd{t}
      </me>.
      Now, use integration by parts to find the antiderivative of <m>t e^t</m>.
    </p>
  </statement>

  <solution>
    <p>
      Let <m>f = t</m> and <m>g = e^t</m>.
      Then, <m>\dot{f} = 1</m> and <m>\dot{g} = e^t</m>.
      Using the formula for integration by parts, we get
      <me>
        \int t e^t \dd{t} = t e^t - \int e^t \dd{t} = t e^t - e^t + C = e^t (t - 1) + C
      </me>.
    </p>
  </solution>
</exercise>
</exercisegroup> </exercises>
